al; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">covering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the first nine months of payment of housing benefits directly to tenants (available here:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/direct-payment-demonstration-project-learning-and-payment-figures"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/direct-payment-demonstration-project-learning-and-payment-figures</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).  Figures in the May press release show 6,168 tenants received direct payments, the total level of rent charged stood at £19,204,022 and an improvement in the average rent collection rate to 94%- with levels of payments by tenants on the projects varying from 91% to 97%. (This compares to an average of 92% published in a December 2012 press release covering the first four months).  The demonstration projects are being independently evaluated (funded by DWP) by a research consortium, from the Centre for Regional Economic and Social Research (CRESR) at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sheffield </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hallam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> University, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Institute of Social Policy at the University of Oxford, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lpsos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> MORI (IM). The evaluation findings, including full rent account analysis and the operation of switch-backs are due to be published in a series of reports in 2014.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:103%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:103%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In response to a question from Bob Blackman on Call-In criteria, Peter Schofield referred the Committee to a </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm121026/wmstext/121026m0001.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Written Ministerial Statement dated October 2012</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on this issue; a copy of that statement is attached to this letter for reference.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>